entry.title: [js-code-coverage] Enable coverage for shared and service workers
entry.content:
DevToolsAgentHost's extend base::RefCounted, when they are spawned for

non-worker types the places they are spawned grab a reference which

ensures the host is kept alive for the duration of the test.



However when a worker type is spawned the callee doesn't get a reference

to the host, this means after attaching the client to the host all

references are lost and the host gets destroyed. This leaves a race

condition where the host gets created, attached and destroyed THEN the

DevtoolsListener tries to start code coverage, however, the host has

been destroyed.



To avoid this race, let's grab a scoped_refptr to the DevToolsAgentHost

to ensure it doesn't get destroyed immediately. Along with this, let's

extend the DevToolsAgentCoverageObserver to log out the destroyed

lifecycle event.



There are a number of tests which have been disabled due to this

functionality, this test also enables all these tests.



Fixed: b/310521014

entry.title: Promise app scale animation in shelf
entry.content:
Refactors the animation to replace a promise app with the installed app

item in shelf. Instead of copying the promise app view layer tree and

cross-fading the actual app view into the shelf, the promise item is

hidden immediately while the installed app item UI is initialized to

simulate promise app state - i.e. the icon is scaled down and the

progress indicator is shown. The app button view is then animated into

the final (default) app state. This makes animating more flexible, as it

enables animating the progress ring and the app icon view independently.



To prevent jankiness caused by delayed app icon load, the installed app

icon view is initialized to use the icon from the promise app. The icon

is then replaced after the scale in animation completes, and the actual

icon loads. Without this, there would be a flash of an empty icon just

after the promise app is hidden, and the installed app icon is shown.

entry.title: DOM: Fix Observable re-entrancy bug
entry.content:
Observables have a strict requirement that `complete()` and `error()`

can only ever be called once, and specifically, once either one of these

runs, no other `Observer` method can ever run again.



The experimental Observable implementation in Blink previously did not

respect this constraint, and this CL fixes this by essentially "closing"

the subscription.



===Subsequent work===



Properly "closing" a subscription involves:

1. Ensuring `Subscriber#isActive` becomes false

(https://github.com/WICG/observable/issues/76 will track this).

2. Aborting the Subscriber's `AbortSignal`. This requires the

AbortSignal that lives on `Subscriber` to differ from the one

passed into `subscribe()`. See crrev.com/c/5017401.

3. Running the teardowns as the AbortSignal algorithms. Future CLs

will implement the `addTeardown()` method in accordance with

discussion in

https://github.com/WICG/observable/issues/22#issuecomment-1805840402.



R=masonf@chromium.org

entry.title: Feedback UI: Add initial test setup and tests.
entry.content:
Prod code changes:

- Put chrome.getVariableValue() calls behind FeedbackBrowserProxy.

- Put navigator.webkitGetUserMedia() call behind

FeedbackBrowserProxy. This call was causing problems during tests

in both CrOS (dangling pointer crash) and LaCrOS

(http://crbug.com/1501422).

- Allow FeedbackBrowserProxy instance to be replaced with

TestFeedbackBrowserProxy in tests, before the prod

code dereferences FeedbackBrowserProxyImple.getInstance().

- Provide an explicit 'ready-for-testing' event for when the UI is

ready for testing (after all async updates have finished).



Test code changes:

- Implement a TestFeedbackBrowserProxy.

- Add FeedbackBrowserTest class with one non-trivial test case.



Note that FeedbackHandler is only registered when this WebUI is

triggered as part of its parent native dialog in FeedbackDialog. Without

the TestFeedbackBrowserProxy the tests would fail with an "Unhandled

chrome.send" error, since the FeedbackHandler is not registered at all

in the test context (which is just loading chrome://feedback in a

regular tab).



Regradless of the above, the ability to intercept calls to the backend is necessary to add more exhaustive WebUI tests in follow up CLs.



Lastly, the unconventional approach for performing test setup before

the prod code runs, is necessary due to this WebUI still not using

web components, and therefore not making it easy to programmatically

create the UI on demand. It can be simplified when/if this WebUI is

componetized.

entry.title: Fix trackers for element-under-pointer after node deletion
entry.content:
This CL fixes, behind an experimental flag, how MouseEventManager and

PointerEventManager tracks the element under mouse pointer following

a DOM modification. The tracker is used for the dispatch of the

boundary events (pointerover, pointerout, pointerenter, pointerleave

to a deleted element which is a no-op further down the event path.

These dropped events caused broken pairing of out/over and

enter/leave events on the JS side. Re-attaching a deleted

entry.title: view-transition: Fix snapshot CB calculation on Android
entry.content:
As a result of https://crbug.com/1478653, the snapshot root calculation

was changed to be based on LayoutView::ClientWidth/Height. This seems to

be the correct way to access the layout-computed content area,

accounting for a scrollbar-gutter. However, this broke the case where a

page is wider than its initial-containing-block. In that case, the

LayoutView will be (much) smaller than the FrameView but the FrameView

is what's filling the visual viewport (when fully zoomed out).



This CL restores the FrameView-based calculation removed by fixing bug

1478653 but keeps the LayoutView calculation if ViewportEnabled is off,

that is, the computation depends on whether or not the FrameView and

LayoutView can differ in size (this is effectively an IsAndroid switch).

I don't think there's currently a simple value for this in the layout

system. While not the most satisfying fix, scrollbar-gutters and

viewport-behavior are mutually exclusive as the latter implies

non-zoomable overlay scrollbars.



This fixes the DCHECKs being tripped in 1495157 which revealed the

problem. It also removes the DCHECKs about the snapshot root being

smaller than the max texture size. The fixed viewport can be up to 4

times the size of device viewport (since the absolute minimum scale

allowed is 0.25) which can sometimes exceed the max texture size.



Bug: 1495157,1478653
